WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.746 --> 00:00:15.236
We're at a tipping point in human history,
我们身处人类历史的转折点上，

2
00:00:15.236 --> 00:00:20.763
a species poised between gaining the stars and losing the planet we call home.
人类处在想获得其他星球，同时也在失去地球家园的尴尬境地。

3
00:00:21.152 --> 00:00:23.882
Even in just the past few years, we've greatly expanded
即使是在过去短短几年的时间里，我们对地球

4
00:00:23.882 --> 00:00:28.212
our knowledge of how Earth fits within the context of our universe.
是如何在宇宙中存在的认识已经有了大幅度的提升。

5
00:00:28.212 --> 00:00:30.950
NASA's Kepler mission has discovered
美国国家航空航天局的开普勒任务已经发现了

6
00:00:30.950 --> 00:00:33.899
thousands of potential planets around other stars,
围绕着其他恒星的数千颗潜在的行星，

7
00:00:33.899 --> 00:00:38.093
indicating that Earth is but one of billions of planets in our galaxy.
这也表明了地球只是银河系中数十亿行星中的一颗。

8
00:00:38.093 --> 00:00:39.963
Kepler is a space telescope
开普勒是个太空望远镜，

9
00:00:39.963 --> 00:00:44.254
that measures the subtle dimming of stars as planets pass in front of them,
它可以发现行星在经过恒星前方发生“凌日现象”，

10
00:00:44.254 --> 00:00:47.102
blocking just a little bit of that light from reaching us.
挡住到达我们这里的光时，光线发生的细微变化。

11
00:00:47.552 --> 00:00:50.152
Kepler's data reveals planets' sizes
开普勒望远镜的数据揭示了行星的大小，

12
00:00:50.152 --> 00:00:52.938
as well as their distance from their parent star.
以及它们与其母恒星之间的距离。

13
00:00:52.938 --> 00:00:56.978
Together, this helps us understand whether these planets are small and rocky,
把这些综合起来就可以帮助我们理解这些行星是否像太阳系中

14
00:00:56.978 --> 00:00:59.533
like the terrestrial planets in our own Solar System,
那些类地行星一样，体积小，而且岩石密布，

15
00:00:59.533 --> 00:01:02.899
and also how much light they receive from their parent sun.
以及我们从它们的母恒星那里得到了多少光。

16
00:01:02.899 --> 00:01:09.238
In turn, this provides clues as to whether these planets that we discover might be habitable or not.
同时，这也能为我们判断已找到的那些行星是否适宜居住提供了一些线索。

17
00:01:09.238 --> 00:01:13.301
Unfortunately, at the same time as we're discovering this treasure trove
但不幸的是，在我们极力去探索潜在的宜居星球，

18
00:01:13.301 --> 00:01:15.414
of potentially habitable worlds,
这些“无主宝藏”的同时，

19
00:01:15.414 --> 00:01:18.874
our own planet is sagging under the weight of humanity.
我们自己的星球却正遭受着人类的破坏。

20
00:01:18.874 --> 00:01:23.286
2014 was the hottest year on record.
2014年是有记录以来最热的一年。

21
00:01:23.286 --> 00:01:26.629
Glaciers and sea ice that have been with us for millennia
冰川和海上的浮冰跟我们一起相处了几千年，

22
00:01:26.629 --> 00:01:29.764
are now disappearing in a matter of decades.
但在过去几十年的时间里却正在逐渐消失。

23
00:01:29.764 --> 00:01:34.875
These planetary-scale environmental  changes that we have set in motion
这些我们所造成的全球性环境变化的速度，

24
00:01:34.875 --> 00:01:38.347
are rapidly outpacing our ability to alter their course.
远远超过了我们拯救环境的速度。

25
00:01:39.167 --> 00:01:42.882
But I'm not a climate scientist, I'm an astronomer.
但我不是气候学家，我是个天文学家。

26
00:01:42.882 --> 00:01:46.252
I study planetary habitability as influenced by stars
我研究在恒星影响下行星的宜居性，

27
00:01:46.252 --> 00:01:48.710
with the hopes of finding the places in the universe
希望可以在宇宙中找到

28
00:01:48.710 --> 00:01:51.682
where we might discover life beyond our own planet.
除地球以外，有生命存在的地方。

29
00:01:51.682 --> 00:01:55.222
You could say that I look for choice alien real estate.
也可以说我是在寻找外星的房地产。

30
00:01:55.722 --> 00:02:00.064
Now, as somebody who is deeply embedded in the search for life in the universe,
现在，作为一个刻苦钻研，想要找寻宇宙中的生命体的人，

31
00:02:00.064 --> 00:02:03.431
I can tell you that the more you look for planets like Earth,
我可以告诉大家，你越想找到像地球一样的行星，

32
00:02:03.431 --> 00:02:07.077
the more you appreciate our own planet itself.
你就会越珍惜我们自己的星球。

33
00:02:07.077 --> 00:02:09.770
Each one of these new worlds invites a comparison
我们每发现一处“新大陆”，就会对这些新发现的星球

34
00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:15.482
between the newly discovered planet and the planets we know best: those of our own Solar System.
和那些太阳系中我们最熟悉的行星做一个比较。

35
00:02:15.482 --> 00:02:17.444
Consider our neighbor, Mars.
想想我们的邻居，火星。

36
00:02:17.444 --> 00:02:21.229
Mars is small and rocky, and though it's a bit far from the Sun,
火星很小，表面布满岩石，虽然它离太阳有点远，

37
00:02:21.229 --> 00:02:23.754
it might be considered a potentially habitable world
但如果从类似开普勒任务的角度来看，

38
00:02:23.754 --> 00:02:25.756
if found by a mission like Kepler.
可能会认为它是个宜居的世界。

39
00:02:25.756 --> 00:02:29.123
Indeed, it's possible that Mars was habitable in the past,
事实上，火星在过去的确有可能是适宜居住的，

40
00:02:29.123 --> 00:02:32.560
and in part, this is why we study Mars so much.
这也是我们为什么对火星投入这么多研究精力的一部分原因。

41
00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:35.950
Our rovers, like Curiosity, crawl across its surface,
我们的那些火星车，比如好奇者号，爬过火星的表面，

42
00:02:35.950 --> 00:02:39.200
scratching for clues as to the origins of life as we know it.
寻找我们所知的生命起源的迹象。

43
00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:42.706
Orbiters like the MAVEN mission sample the Martian atmosphere,
进行“火星大气与挥发物演化任务”（MAVEN）的人造卫星采集了火星的大气样本，

44
00:02:42.706 --> 00:02:46.398
trying to understand how Mars might have lost its past habitability.
试着了解火星是如何失去曾经的可居住性的。

45
00:02:46.398 --> 00:02:50.963
Private spaceflight companies now offer not just a short trip to near space
私人太空旅行公司现在不仅仅提供近太空的短程旅行，

46
00:02:50.963 --> 00:02:54.664
but the tantalizing possibility of living our lives on Mars.
还提供了可以在火星上居住的诱人的可能性。

47
00:02:54.664 --> 00:02:56.614
But though these Martian vistas
尽管火星上的这些远景看起来

48
00:02:56.614 --> 00:02:59.169
resemble the deserts of our own home world,
很像我们地球上的沙漠，

49
00:02:59.169 --> 00:03:04.741
places that are tied in our imagination to ideas about pioneering and frontiers,
那些一提到就会联想起拓荒者、边境等等的地方，

50
00:03:04.741 --> 00:03:06.413
compared to Earth
但与地球相比，

51
00:03:06.413 --> 00:03:09.710
Mars is a pretty terrible place to live.
火星上的环境对于生命体来说简直太恶劣了。

52
00:03:09.710 --> 00:03:14.888
Consider the extent to which we have not colonized the deserts of our own planet,
想想那些我们还没有征服的地球上的沙漠，

53
00:03:14.888 --> 00:03:17.721
places that are lush by comparison with Mars.
相较于火星来说，沙漠可都算是“枝繁叶茂”了，

54
00:03:17.721 --> 00:03:20.507
Even in the driest, highest places on Earth,
即使在地球上最干燥海拔最高的地方，

55
00:03:20.507 --> 00:03:23.107
the air is sweet and thick with oxygen
我们仍然能呼吸到数千英里外

56
00:03:23.107 --> 00:03:27.194
exhaled from thousands of miles away by our rainforests.
那些热带雨林生产出的新鲜的、富含氧气的空气。

57
00:03:27.194 --> 00:03:33.138
I worry -- I worry that this excitement about colonizing Mars and other planets
我担心——我担心殖民于火星和其他行星的激动之情

58
00:03:33.138 --> 00:03:36.249
carries with it a long, dark shadow:
会带来深远的负面影响：

59
00:03:36.249 --> 00:03:38.269
the implication and belief by some
源于一些人的心理暗示和信仰——

60
00:03:38.269 --> 00:03:41.822
that Mars will be there to save us from the self-inflicted destruction
认为火星将会是我们自己把唯一真正宜居的行星，地球

61
00:03:41.822 --> 00:03:45.955
of the only truly habitable planet we know of, the Earth.
毁灭之后的“诺亚方舟”。

62
00:03:45.955 --> 00:03:48.393
As much as I love interplanetary exploration,
这么说吧，我有多爱星际探索，

63
00:03:48.393 --> 00:03:50.738
I deeply disagree with this idea.
我就有多反对这种想法。

64
00:03:50.738 --> 00:03:53.431
There are many excellent reasons to go to Mars,
去火星有很多天花乱坠的理由，

65
00:03:53.431 --> 00:03:56.845
but for anyone to tell you that Mars will be there to back up humanity
但如果有人跟你说火星是个人类生存地的备胎的话，

66
00:03:56.845 --> 00:03:59.953
is like the captain of the Titanic telling you that the real party
那就像泰坦尼克号的船长告诉你，“一会儿真正的派对

67
00:03:59.953 --> 00:04:02.324
is happening later on the lifeboats.
将在救生船上展开”一样的胡扯。

68
00:04:02.324 --> 00:04:05.273
(Laughter)
（笑声）

69
00:04:05.273 --> 00:04:08.175
(Applause)
（掌声）

70
00:04:08.175 --> 00:04:10.962
Thank you.
谢谢。

71
00:04:10.962 --> 00:04:14.748
But the goals of interplanetary exploration and planetary preservation
然而，事实上星际探索和保护星球这两个目标

72
00:04:14.748 --> 00:04:16.929
are not opposed to one another.
并不互相矛盾。

73
00:04:16.929 --> 00:04:19.460
No, they're in fact two sides of the same goal:
实际上，它们是同一个目标的两个方面：

74
00:04:19.460 --> 00:04:23.802
to understand, preserve and improve life into the future.
那就是了解、保护和改善生命，使生命延续。

75
00:04:23.802 --> 00:04:27.865
The extreme environments of our own world are alien vistas.
我们星球上的极端环境就是外星的景象。

76
00:04:27.865 --> 00:04:29.746
They're just closer to home.
只是它们离我们比较近而已。

77
00:04:29.746 --> 00:04:33.925
If we can understand how to create and maintain habitable spaces
如果我们能知道如何在地球上十分恶劣，不宜居住的环境中

78
00:04:33.925 --> 00:04:37.315
out of hostile, inhospitable spaces here on Earth,
创造并维持可居住的空间，

79
00:04:37.315 --> 00:04:42.981
perhaps we can meet the needs of both preserving our own environment and moving beyond it.
也许我们就能满足既保护我们的环境，又“走出去”的双重需求了。

80
00:04:42.981 --> 00:04:45.291
I leave you with a final thought experiment:
最后我想给大家出一个思考题：

81
00:04:45.291 --> 00:04:46.986
Fermi's paradox.
“费米悖论”。

82
00:04:46.986 --> 00:04:51.848
Many years ago, the physicist Enrico Fermi asked that, given the fact
许多年前，物理学家恩里科·费米提出了一个问题：那就是，

83
00:04:51.848 --> 00:04:54.695
that our universe has been around for a very long time
我们的宇宙存在了很长很长的时间是个事实，

84
00:04:54.695 --> 00:04:57.365
and we expect that there are many planets within it,
我们也知道宇宙中有无数的行星，

85
00:04:57.365 --> 00:05:00.453
we should have found evidence for alien life by now.
那我们现在应该已经找到外星生命存在的迹象了。

86
00:05:00.453 --> 00:05:02.496
So where are they?
可是它们在哪呢？

87
00:05:02.496 --> 00:05:05.863
Well, one possible solution to Fermi's paradox
“费米悖论”的一种可能的解释是这样的：

88
00:05:05.863 --> 00:05:09.346
is that, as civilizations become technologically advanced enough
随着文明的进步，科技变得足够先进，

89
00:05:09.346 --> 00:05:11.668
to consider living amongst the stars,
能够开始考虑如何在宇宙中生存时，

90
00:05:11.668 --> 00:05:14.152
they lose sight of how important it is
人们也就会忽视

91
00:05:14.152 --> 00:05:18.680
to safeguard the home worlds that fostered that advancement to begin with.
保护自己的家园，这个孕育了高科技的地方的重要性。

92
00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:23.068
It is hubris to believe that interplanetary colonization alone
简单地迷信殖民于其他星球就可以拯救我们自己

93
00:05:23.068 --> 00:05:24.949
will save us from ourselves,
恐怕是自不量力，

94
00:05:24.949 --> 00:05:30.372
but planetary preservation and interplanetary exploration can work together.
其实环境保护和星际探索这两项工作是可以结合着进行的。

95
00:05:30.372 --> 00:05:32.495
If we truly believe in our ability
如果我们对为了人类居住

96
00:05:32.495 --> 00:05:36.001
to bend the hostile environments of Mars for human habitation,
而改变火星恶劣环境的能力足够自信的话，

97
00:05:36.001 --> 00:05:41.760
then we should be able to surmount the far easier task of preserving the habitability of the Earth.
那我们更应该可以完成保护地球宜居性这个超级简单的任务。

98
00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:42.806
Thank you.
谢谢。

99
00:05:42.816 --> 00:05:49.336
(Applause)
（掌声）